# 007 — Element groups, experiment collections, multiple detectors & undo/redo participation

## Spec reference

- `C:\GitHub\Berreman\specs\0026\.spec-md` — parent spec this slice belongs to
  (Spec 0026 — Optical Constructor UI). This slice realises **Part G**
  (element groups, multiple detectors, separate storage), **Part H**
  (experiment collections [Should]), and **Part K** (undo/redo participation
  and safety [Must]). As the final slice it carries the full bundle gate set.
- Depends on slice 001 (`Placement.fs`), slice 004 (storage/schema patterns),
  slice 005 (`Commands.fs`, `ConstructorView.fs`), and slice 006 (ribbon
  *Experiment* tab, element context menu).

## Inherited from parent spec

### Binding constraints (from `.spec-md` ## 0)

0.1 **Reuse the engine, do not re‑type it.** The constructor MUST drive the
existing beam tree (`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Domain/BeamTree.fs:35`
defines `ConstructorElement`; `:53` defines `BeamNode`; `:91` `solve`;
`:117` `routeAndSolve`) and the project aggregate
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Domain/Project.fs:26`,
`OpticalConstructorProject`). It MUST NOT introduce a parallel element
catalogue, a parallel solver, or a parallel project type.

0.2 **Canonical SI everywhere.** Every stored physical magnitude (table
dimensions, placement‑point coordinates, distances along rays, box
dimensions) MUST be held in canonical SI base units (meters), matching the
units spine (`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Domain/Units.fs:20`,
`UnitOfMeasure`; `:43` `toMeters`; `:71` `fromMeters`). Unit conversion
happens ONLY at the display / import / export boundary through that module;
no other module hand‑rolls a conversion. Each element and the table MAY
carry a per‑object preferred display unit (display metadata only, mirroring
`BeamNode.defaultUnit`, BeamTree.fs:59).

0.3 **Pure, serializable MVU models; public FuncUI surface only.** All new
view models MUST be pure and serializable F# values (no Avalonia handle,
renderer instance, or cancellation token in a model), matching the existing
root model (`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/Shell.fs:94`,
`RootModel`). All view code MUST be authored against the public MIT
`Avalonia.FuncUI` NuGet DSL surface used today. The audit‑gated FuncUI clone
at `C:/GitHub/Avalonia.FuncUI.Clone/` MUST NOT be referenced, linked, or
built (`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/AppShell.fs:8`
records the gate). Geometry MUST be expressed as pure projections carrying
no Avalonia type, so every geometry rule is provable headless, exactly as
the existing schematic does
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/Schematic.fs:18`).

0.4 **Single source of commands — declared once, surfaced twice.** Two
distinct command surfaces in this spec MUST each be driven from one
declaration, never wired twice:
- the **ribbon ↔ drop‑down menu** pairing (Part D): a command appears in
  both the ribbon and the collapsed‑ribbon menus from one definition;
- the **keyboard ↔ mouse** pairing (Part E): a command reachable by both a
  key and a mouse gesture declares both bindings on one definition.
Both surfaces MUST read from the centralized command registry of Part E.

0.5 **Schematic, not physical‑grade.** The on‑table drawing is a schematic.
Ray bending through tilted elements MUST use a fixed refractive index of
`n = 1.0` outside an element and `n = 1.5` inside, applying Snell's law to
position the drawn lines (Part B). The schematic MUST stay consistent with
which branches the engine beam tree actually computes (reflected /
transmitted), but it MUST NOT attempt physical‑optics accuracy.

0.6 **Plausible‑expansion exclusions.** A downstream implementer MUST NOT
add, unless a directive in this spec names it: caching or a retained‑mode
scene graph for the table render; a drawing‑backend abstraction layer;
schema migration or version‑upgrade code (every install starts from a
blank slate; a schema‑version mismatch is a validation error, matching
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/schema/optical-constructor-project.schema.json:12`);
a real device/material picker behind the value‑id binding action (Part F
commits only an empty modal); physical‑grade ray tracing; a third language
beyond the EN/RU resource mechanism (the *mechanism* MUST support adding
one by editing a file, but no third language ships).

0.7 **Net‑new vs reused.** The following are **net‑new** (verified absent
today): element placement (position, the three rotations, bounding box,
normals, drawer), the ray‑group model and snapping, the top‑down table
surface, the ribbon/menu shell, the centralized command model, EN/RU
localization (no `CultureInfo`‑based localization, `ResourceManager`, or
`.resx` exists; the only `CultureInfo` uses are `InvariantCulture` number
parsing), the standardized‑controls module, element groups, and experiment
collections. The following are **reused as‑is**: the beam‑tree solver
(BeamTree.fs:91), the units spine (Units.fs), JSON project storage
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/ProjectFile.fs:20`
`saveProject`, `:31` `openProject`), schema validation
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/SchemaValidation.fs:61`
`validate`), snapshot undo/redo
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/History.fs:20`
`EditHistory`), and the environment/settings store
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/UserEnvironment.fs:141`
`EnvironmentSettings`).

### Acceptance criteria owned by this slice

- AC‑G1: A mutually‑exclusive group allows at most one member in the beam
  (choosing one removes the others); a multi‑select group allows zero/one/
  several; both preserve every member's stored configuration across a swap
  (G.1).
- AC‑G2: With more than one detector, the user can set the primary; the
  headline readout follows the primary while secondary detectors report
  their own branch (G.2).
- AC‑G3: Groups and collections round‑trip through the separate app‑data
  JSON file with schema validation, independent of any `.ocproj` (G.3).
- AC‑H1: An experiment collection groups experiments around shared
  sample(s), supports on/off across the collection, and round‑trips through
  the groups/collections JSON (H.1).
- AC‑K1: Each of placement, rotation, lock toggle, group on/off, swap, and
  detector change pushes a snapshot so `Ctrl+Z` reverses it and `Ctrl+Y`
  replays it, across more than one level (K.1).
- AC‑K2: Reset rotation, delete element, and reset view are each either
  undoable or confirmation‑gated with same‑row distinct‑colour Confirm/Cancel
  (K.2).

