## Scope

This slice completes the feature with three things. **Part G/H:** element
groups (a named set of member elements, each holding its full
configuration), the two member modes (mutually exclusive / multi‑select),
multiple detectors with a user‑chosen primary, experiment collections around
shared samples, and a separate per‑user app‑data JSON file (with its own
schema) for groups + collections, kept apart from the per‑project `.ocproj`.
**Part K:** wiring every constructor model edit that changes the project to
`push` a snapshot onto the shared `EditHistory`, keeping undo/redo
multi‑level, and the safety gate on destructive actions. Because all
project‑mutating actions (placement, rotation, lock, group on/off, swap,
detector add/remove, set‑primary, table resize, light‑source move/reset) now
exist after slices 001–006, this final slice is where AC‑K1/AC‑K2 can be
satisfied end‑to‑end.

## Requirements

### R-1. Group model and member modes (G.1)

G.1.1 A new module
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Domain/Groups.fs` MUST
define an `ElementGroup` as a named set of member elements, each member
holding its **full configuration** (its placement, rotations, value id,
emission metadata). The group MUST be placeable on, or removable from, the
central‑ray path as a unit.

G.1.2 Each group MUST be one of two member modes, chosen per group:
- **Mutually exclusive** — at most one member may be in the beam at a time;
  choosing one MUST automatically take the others out of the beam.
- **Multi‑select** — zero, one, or several members may be in the beam at
  once.
Either way the group MUST remember all members and their settings; the
on/off and swap choices MUST change only which members are currently in the
beam, never their stored configuration.

G.1.3 Groups MUST be nameable and reusable, building on the existing
favourites concept (`FavoriteGroup`, UserEnvironment.fs:126) so a commonly
used group can be pinned and dropped back in later.

### R-2. Multiple detectors and the primary one (G.2)

G.2.1 The primary path normally ends in one detector, but the user MUST be
able to place more than one detector when a branch (e.g. a reflected arm)
needs its own. When there is more than one, the user MUST choose which
detector is the primary one (Part E "Set as primary"). Results and the
headline readout MUST follow the primary detector; secondary detectors MUST
report their own branch independently (consistent with each branch carrying
its own field, BeamTree.fs:98).

### R-3. Separate groups/collections storage (G.3)

G.3.1 Element groups and experiment collections (Part H) MUST be stored in
their own separate JSON file, kept apart from the per‑project `.ocproj`
file, so reusable groups and sample‑centred collections are available
across projects. A new module
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/GroupsLibrary.fs`
MUST own this file's load/save, reusing the shared JSON options and the
schema‑validate‑on‑load seam (SchemaValidation.fs:61), with a new schema
file
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/schema/optical-constructor-groups.schema.json`.

G.3.2 The groups/collections file MUST live at a fixed per‑user
application‑data path, mirroring the environment store's location
convention (UserEnvironment.fs:279, the `Softellect/Berreman/OpticalConstructor`
app‑data folder). Because that path is outside the repository working tree,
this file raises no `.gitignore` collision (constraint check satisfied: the
committable‑state cross‑check is moot for an app‑data file; were it ever
placed in‑tree, a `*.json` name does not collide with any root `.gitignore`
pattern such as `*.cache`/`*.log`/`*.tmp`/`[Bb]in/`/`[Oo]bj/`).

### R-4. Reuse before invention for storage (G.4)

Reuse the JSON options and validation seam used by the project and
environment stores (SchemaValidation.fs:61; UserEnvironment.fs:185
defaults/load/save pattern) rather than a new serializer; reuse the
`FavoriteGroup` notion (UserEnvironment.fs:126) for pin/reuse.

### R-5. Collection model (H.1)

H.1.1 `Groups.fs` (R-1) MUST define an `ExperimentCollection` as a named
set of experiments sharing the same sample(s), with the user able to turn
elements and groups on and off across the collection. Collections MUST be
stored in the same separate JSON file as groups (G.3) and MUST round‑trip
through it.

### R-6. Every constructor action is a snapshot edit (K.1)

K.1.1 Every constructor model edit that changes the project (placement,
each rotation, each lock toggle, group on/off, swap, detector add/remove,
set‑primary, table resize, light‑source move/reset) MUST `push` the new
project onto the shared `EditHistory` (History.fs:33), so `Ctrl+Z` /
`Ctrl+Y` (Part E.6) step through them.

K.1.2 Undo and redo MUST be multi‑level (History.fs is a multi‑level
zipper); the constructor MUST NOT degrade it to single‑level.

### R-7. Safety on destructive actions (K.2)

K.2.1 Destructive or hard‑to‑reverse actions (reset rotation, delete
element, reset view) MUST either be undoable through K.1 or ask for
confirmation, consistent with the `Shift+R`‑with‑confirmation behaviour
(Part E.2). Any opposing‑action pair (Confirm/Cancel) MUST be same‑row with
a visible gap and distinct positive‑CTA / negative‑CTA colours (Part J.2 /
ConstructionView.fs:40).

### R-8. Reuse before invention for history (K.3)

Reuse `History.fs` (History.fs:20) as the undo/redo carrier; do not add a
command‑pattern diff log or a parallel history.

### R-9. UX commitments completed here (UX 5, UX 6)

- UX 5 — Opposing actions (Confirm/Cancel on reset/delete) MUST be same‑row,
  with a visible gap and distinct positive/negative colours (J.2). Every
  action that moves or deletes user‑visible state MUST be undoable via
  `EditHistory` (K.1) — the undo affordance, not a separate recent‑actions
  panel.
- UX 6 — The only new persisted operator state is the groups/collections
  JSON, placed at the per‑user app‑data path outside the repository (G.3.2),
  so no `.gitignore` collision is possible; `.ocproj` user documents remain
  committable and are explicitly never git‑ignored (ProjectFile.fs:14).

## Non-requirements

- No schema migration / version‑upgrade code for the groups file (0.6).
- No command‑pattern diff log or parallel history (K.3) — reuse
  `History.fs`.
- No new serializer for the groups library (G.4) — reuse the shared JSON
  options / validation seam.
- No third member mode beyond mutually‑exclusive and multi‑select (G.1.2).

